<br>
Then, I tie up the drumsticks with some cooking string and put that bad boy on top of a bed of cut up celery, onion and baby carrots.<br>
<br>
Cook it in the oven first for 45 minutes at 375 degrees.<br>
<br>
Then, crank it up to 425 degrees for 15 to 30 minutes more.  Just make sure to check the temperature with a thermometer to ensure that it's cooked all the way through.<br>
<br>
I got this recipe from some cooking show I watched.  Turns out pretty nice.  Good and flavorful.   Plus you have instant veggies for it too.   <br>
<br>
You can turn the crusty bits at the bottom into an au jus with some chicken broth and the pan juices.  But I don't bother usually.  <br>
<br>
Avoid poking the chicken more than you have to.  The more holes you put in it, the more the juices escape.<br>
<br>
What's also good is drunken chicken.  Give the bird a good buttering and herbing and then shove half a can of beer up its behind.  Grill it sitting up on indirect heat for an hour and a half.  Or put it (sitting up) on a roasting pan and follow the oven roasting instructions from above.  Some chile powder and cumin for the &quot;herbing&quot; gives it a nice southwestern edge. <p><center><table>
