<br>
First, get Strong Male Type to remove icky stuff from inside bird. This usually accomplished by use of the devestating Double Blink Chin Quiver and a comment to the effect that the sooner it gets done, the sooner it gets cooked and he can eat.<br>
<br>
Then, rinse the bird under the tap and check for pinfeathers. You'd be amazed at how often they leave a few feathers on.<br>
<br>
Next, put birdy on a counter and put a stick of butter and generous smattering of rosemary and garlic in a bowl and squich it all together. Fresh yummy herbs are SO much better for this, just mince em fine.<br>
<br>
next, shove some of the butter up the birdy's behind along with a very small onion quartered. Very small. Better yet, go the whole route and use 2 small shallots quartered. Mr. Birdy loves having shallot shoved up inside him the kinky fellow.<br>
<br>
Ok, now the FUN part! Tie up mr birdy like an offering to the Almighty Bondage God. Tie his little legs together (can't have him jumping out of the pan!) and bend his wingtips behind his back. They normally don't need tying, but if you really want to he won't complain!<br>
<br>
Take the rest of the butter and liberally spread it all over the bird. It helps him get a nice tan.<br>
<br>
Place bird wingside down (breast up) in a roasting pan. Preferably with a rack, but if you don't have one don't worry about it.<br>
<br>
If you like roasted veggies with your bird, scatter some onions, carrots, and potatos around him.<br>
<br>
Then throw the whole kitncaboodle in the oven and turn it on. Medium highish is what I usually used... ok, actually I just spun the dial till I felt like stopping. Lottery style. Sometimes I even wore clo... err, nevermind.<br>
<br>
Leave mr bird alone.. don't poke him, prod him, open his door, or anything like that more than you absolutely HAVE to.<br>
<br>
After a while... usually one backpack of celestial essences and scents of marr... test him by grabbing his legs with a potholder and gently moving them. If they move easy, he's prolly done. To test, stick a fork in his thigh... juices should run clear. Don't poke him too often, that's just a second test. If he appears done, take him from the oven, set him on a carving board and WALK AWAY!!!! Do not even LOOK at mr bird for 15-20 minutes... it lets his juices distribute through the meat instead of through the kitchen.<br>
<br>
While you wait, if you want, make a simple chicken gravy by draining most the grease from the pan, adding some canned chicken broth, and stirring all the crispy bits off the bottom of the pan. Then make a mixture of a little cornstarch and some water (about a half cup of water and a tablespoon of cornstarch is what I use, but if you like a thinner/thicker gravy adjust the cornstarch down/up.) Pour that in and whisk until it comes back to a boil (just stick the pan on a burner... easier than pouring it in a saucepan). Taste it and add salt, pepper, etc etc etc until you're happy.<br>
<br>
By now, Mr Bird is all rested and relaxed and you can remove the strings, carve him up, and serve him with some yummy garlic smashed redskin potatos, green and wax beans with a gentle coating of butter, salt, and pepper, a nice tea, coffee, or the ever popular orange kool-aid (reccomended for all chicken! teehee!) and a nice strawberry shortcake for dessert 8)<br>
<br>
Strawberry shortcake is very VERY complex...<br>
<br>
A few hours ahead of time...<br>
Cut up strawberries. Slices, quarters, large chunks, whatever.<br>
Put strawberries in bowl.<br>
Pour sugar (about a cup or so is what I use... but then, I also use an entire flat of strawberries.) on berries.<br>
Toss in a split vanilla bean, little splish of vanilla extract, or your favorite liquor (I use amaretto for some reason)<br>
Stir to coat.<br>
Throw bowl in fridge.<br>
<br>
Shortly before serving...<br>
Make whipped cream<br>
Open package of shortcake cups, lady fingers, poundcake, or angel food cake. Or if you're adventurous, make em yourself!<br>
Put a cake piece or couple of lady fingers in a bowl.<br>
Spoon a bunch of berries and juices over top<br>
Add whipped cream<br>
add another cake<br>
add more berries.<br>
add more whipped cream.<br>
<br>
Eat.<br>
<br>
The BEST part about this meal? it looks gourmet but is so simple my cat can prolly make it. I know he can eat it... never turn your back on a chicken when you have a cat...<br>
